    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Generally refers to a rather rough imitation of incised Coromandel lacquer made in England in the 17th century. In 17th- and early 18th-century literature the term sometimes refers to the genuine article as well.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000011151/Fleming and Honour, Penguin Dictionary of the Decorative Arts (1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Verwijst in algemene zin naar een nogal grove imitatie van ingesneden Coromandel-lakwerk, gemaakt in de 17de eeuw in Engeland. In de 17de- en 18de-eeuwse literatuur verwijst de term soms ook naar echt Coromandel-lakwerk.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>一般指仿造17世紀英格蘭科羅曼德雕花漆器(Coromandel lacquer)的製品。17世紀至18世紀早期的文獻中，此詞彙有時也指真品。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Verweist üblicherweise auf eine eher grobe Immitation des  geritzen Koromandellacks aus dem England des 17. Jahrhunderts. In der Literatur des 17. und frühen 18. Jahrhundert bezieht sich diese Bezeichnung manchmal auch auf das originale Verfahren.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
